<div class="post-content">

<h2>Gameplay Mechanics</h2>
<p>The core loop is familiar to any FNAF player: survive the night by monitoring cameras and closing doors. But TRTBN introduces a generator heat system that replaces the traditional power meter. Every time you close a door, the generator heats up. Let it overheat and both doors lock open until it cools back down. This forces you to be strategic about when to seal off an entrance — sometimes it's better to wait and confirm an animatronic's position than to panic-close a door and risk overheating at the wrong moment.</p>

<p>Instead of fixed door lights, you have a handheld flashlight that must be manually aimed left, right, or behind you. Turning to check one direction means you're blind to the others, creating constant tension as threats can approach from multiple angles simultaneously.</p>

<h3>The Animatronics</h3>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Spring Bonnie (Night 1):</strong> Moves through the cameras to the right hallway. Close the door when you hear him approaching — a classic Bonnie-style pattern to ease you in.</li>
    <li><strong>Fredbear (Night 2):</strong> Mirrors Spring Bonnie's behavior but approaches from the left, functioning as the Chica equivalent.</li>
    <li><strong>The Puppet (Night 3):</strong> Appears behind you in the Prize Corner. Listen for the music box chime and shine your flashlight on it to send it back — similar to Nightmare Freddy's mechanic but with an audio cue.</li>
    <li><strong>Fredbear 2.0 (Night 3):</strong> Approaches the left door directly without using cameras. He's the slowest animatronic and makes audible voice box noises as he creeps closer, giving you a 5-8 second window to react even after he reaches the doorway. Learning to delay your response to him is key to conserving generator heat.</li>
    <li><strong>Spring Bonnie 2.0 (Night 3):</strong> The deadliest threat. He plays a hide-and-seek game through the right-side cameras, progressing through multiple phases in each room. When he reaches his final phase — a terrifying close-up — he'll sprint for your office. He knocks on the door before entering, giving you one last chance to slam it shut. He's fast, lethal, and responsible for most frustrating deaths.</li>
</ul>

<p>Nights 4 through 6 don't introduce new animatronics but ramp up the aggression significantly. The Custom Night lets you face all four main animatronics simultaneously with adjustable AI levels, and maxing it out unlocks a secret ending.</p>

</div>

